#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:-1
msgid ""
"Discover how to create, use, and manage build caches in Spack to share pre-"
"built binary packages and speed up installations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:13
msgid "Build Caches"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:15
msgid ""
"To avoid recompilation of Spack packages, installed packages can be pushed "
"to a build cache, and then downloaded and installed by others."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:17
msgid ""
"Whenever a mirror provides prebuilt packages, Spack will take these packages "
"into account during concretization and installation, making ``spack "
"install`` significantly faster."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:22
msgid ""
"We use the terms \"build cache\" and \"mirror\" often interchangeably. "
"Mirrors are used during installation for both sources and prebuilt packages. "
"Build caches refer to mirrors that provide prebuilt packages."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:28
msgid "Creating a Build Cache"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:30
msgid "Build caches are created via:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:32
msgid "$ spack buildcache push <path/url/mirror name> <spec>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:36
msgid ""
"This command takes the locally installed spec and its dependencies, and "
"creates tarballs of their install prefixes. It also generates metadata "
"files, signed with GPG. These tarballs and metadata files are then pushed to "
"the provided build cache, which can be a local directory or a remote URL."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:40
msgid ""
"Here is an example where a build cache is created in a local directory named "
"\"spack-cache\", to which we push the \"ninja\" spec:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:42
msgid ""
"$ spack buildcache push ./spack-cache ninja\n"
"==> Selected 30 specs to push to file:///home/spackuser/spack/spack-cache\n"
"...\n"
"==> [30/30] Pushed ninja@1.12.1/ngldn2k"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:49
msgid "Note that ``ninja`` must be installed locally for this to work."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:51
msgid ""
"Once you have a build cache, you can add it as a mirror, as discussed next."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:54
msgid "Finding or Installing Build Cache Files"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:56
msgid ""
"To find or install build cache files, a Spack mirror must be configured with:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:58
msgid "$ spack mirror add <name> <url or path>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:63
msgid ""
"Both URLs and local paths on the filesystem can be specified. In the "
"previous example, you might add the directory \"spack-cache\" and call it "
"``mymirror``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:67
msgid "$ spack mirror add mymirror ./spack-cache"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:72
msgid ""
"You can see that the mirror is added with ``spack mirror list`` as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:74
msgid ""
"$ spack mirror list\n"
"mymirror           file:///home/spackuser/spack/spack-cache\n"
"spack-public       https://spack-llnl-mirror.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:82
msgid ""
"At this point, you've created a build cache, but Spack hasn't indexed it, so "
"if you run ``spack buildcache list``, you won't see any results. You need to "
"index this new build cache as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:85
msgid "$ spack buildcache update-index ./spack-cache"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:89
msgid "Now you can use ``list``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:91
msgid ""
"$ spack buildcache list\n"
"==> 24 cached builds.\n"
"-- linux-ubuntu22.04-sapphirerapids / gcc@12.3.0 ----------------\n"
"[ ... ]\n"
"ninja@1.12.1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:99
msgid ""
"With ``mymirror`` configured and an index available, Spack will "
"automatically use it during concretization and installation. That means that "
"you can expect ``spack install ninja`` to fetch prebuilt packages from the "
"mirror. Let's verify by reinstalling ninja:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:103
msgid ""
"$ spack uninstall ninja\n"
"$ spack install ninja\n"
"[ ... ]\n"
"==> Installing ninja-1.12.1-ngldn2kpvb6lqc44oqhhow7fzg7xu7lh [24/24]\n"
"gpg: Signature made Thu 06 Mar 2025 10:03:38 AM MST\n"
"gpg:                using RSA key 75BC0528114909C076E2607418010FFAD73C9B07\n"
"gpg: Good signature from \"example (GPG created for Spack) <example@example."
"com>\" [ultimate]\n"
"==> Fetching file:///home/spackuser/spack/spack-cache/blobs/sha256/f0/"
"f08eb62661ad159d2d258890127fc6053f5302a2f490c1c7f7bd677721010ee0\n"
"==> Fetching file:///home/spackuser/spack/spack-cache/blobs/sha256/c7/"
"c79ac6e40dfdd01ac499b020e52e57aa91151febaea3ad183f90c0f78b64a31a\n"
"==> Extracting ninja-1.12.1-ngldn2kpvb6lqc44oqhhow7fzg7xu7lh from binary "
"cache\n"
"==> ninja: Successfully installed ninja-1.12.1-"
"ngldn2kpvb6lqc44oqhhow7fzg7xu7lh\n"
"  Search: 0.00s.  Fetch: 0.11s.  Install: 0.11s.  Extract: 0.10s.  Relocate: "
"0.00s.  Total: 0.22s\n"
"[+] /home/spackuser/spack/opt/spack/linux-ubuntu22.04-sapphirerapids/"
"gcc-12.3.0/ninja-1.12.1-ngldn2kpvb6lqc44oqhhow7fzg7xu7lh"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:119
msgid ""
"It worked! You've just completed a full example of creating a build cache "
"with a spec of interest, adding it as a mirror, updating its index, listing "
"the contents, and finally, installing from it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:122
msgid ""
"By default, Spack falls back to building from sources when the mirror is not "
"available or when the package is simply not already available. To force "
"Spack to install only prebuilt packages, you can use:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:125
msgid "$ spack install --use-buildcache only <package>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:129
msgid ""
"For example, to combine all of the commands above to add the E4S build cache "
"and then install from it exclusively, you would do:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:131
msgid ""
"$ spack mirror add E4S https://cache.e4s.io\n"
"$ spack buildcache keys --install --trust\n"
"$ spack install --use-buildcache only <package>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:137
msgid ""
"The ``--install`` and ``--trust`` flags install keys to the keyring and "
"trust all downloaded keys."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:141
msgid "Build Cache Index Views"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:144
msgid ""
"Introduced in Spack v1.2. The addition of this feature does not increment "
"the build cache version (v3)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:148
msgid "Build cache index views are not supported in OCI build caches."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:150
msgid ""
"Build caches can quickly become large and inefficient to search as binaries "
"are added over time. A common work around to this problem is to break the "
"build cache into stacks that target specific applications or workflows. This "
"allows for curation of binaries as smaller collections of packages that push "
"to their own mirrors that each maintain a smaller search area. However, this "
"approach comes with the trade off of requiring much larger storage and "
"computational footprints due to duplication of common dependencies between "
"stacks. Splitting build caches can also reduce direct fetch hits by reducing "
"the breadth of binaries available in a single mirror."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:156
msgid ""
"To better address the issues with large search areas, build cache index "
"views (or just \"views\" in this section) were introduced. A view is a named "
"index which provides a curated view into a larger build cache. This allows "
"build cache maintainers to provide the same granularity of build caches "
"split by stacks without having to pay for the extra storage and compute "
"required for the duplicated dependencies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:160
msgid ""
"Views can be created or updated using an active environment, or a list of "
"environment names or paths. The ``spack buildcache`` commands for views are "
"alias of the command ``spack buildcache update-index``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:163
msgid ""
"View indices are stored similarly to the top level build cache index, but "
"use an additional prefix of the view name ``<build cache prefix>/v3/"
"manifests/index/my-stack/index.manifest.json``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:168
msgid "Creating a Build Cache Index View"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:170
msgid "Here is an example of creating a view using an active environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:172
msgid ""
"$ spack env activate my-stack\n"
"$ spack install\n"
"$ spack buildcache push my-mirror\n"
"$ spack buildcache update-index --name my-view my-mirror"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:179
msgid ""
"It is also possible to create a view from a list of one or more environments "
"by passing the environment names or paths. If a list of environments is "
"passed while inside of an active environment, the active environment is "
"ignored and only the passed environments are considered."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:182
msgid ""
"$ spack buildcache update-index --name my-view my-mirror my-stack /path/to/"
"environment/my-other-stack"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:189
msgid "Updating a Build Cache Index View"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:191
msgid ""
"To prevent accidentally overwriting an existing view, it is required to "
"specify how a view should be updated. It is possible to use one of two "
"options for updating a view index: ``--force`` or ``--append``. Using the "
"``--force`` option will replace the index as if the previous one did not "
"exist. The ``--append`` option will first read the existing index, and then "
"add the new specs to it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:196
msgid ""
"$ spack buildcache push my-mirror\n"
"$ spack buildcache update-index --append --name my-view my-mirror my-stack"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:204
msgid ""
"Using the ``--append`` option with build cache index views is a non-atomic "
"operation. In the case where multiple writers are appending to the same "
"view, the result will only include the state of the last to write. When "
"using ``--append`` for build cache workflows it is up to the user to "
"correctly serialize the update operations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:211
msgid "List of Popular Build Caches"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:213
msgid ""
"`Spack Public Build Cache <https://spack.io/>`_: `spack build cache <https://"
"cache.spack.io/>`_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:214
msgid ""
"`Extreme-scale Scientific Software Stack (E4S) <https://e4s-project.github."
"io/>`_: `e4s build cache <https://oaciss.uoregon.edu/e4s/inventory.html>`_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:218
msgid "Creating and Trusting GPG keys"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:223
msgid "``spack gpg``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:225
msgid ""
"Spack has support for signing and verifying packages using GPG keys. A "
"separate keyring is used for Spack, so any keys available in the user's home "
"directory are not used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:229
msgid "``spack gpg init``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:231
msgid ""
"When Spack is first installed, its keyring is empty. Keys stored in :file:"
"`var/spack/gpg` are the default keys for a Spack installation. These keys "
"may be imported by running ``spack gpg init``. This will import the default "
"keys into the keyring as trusted keys."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:237
msgid "Trusting keys"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:239
msgid "Additional keys may be added to the keyring using:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:241
msgid "$ spack gpg trust <keyfile>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:245
msgid ""
"Once a key is trusted, packages signed by the owner of the key may be "
"installed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:247
msgid "To remove keys from your keyring, use:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:249
msgid "$ spack gpg untrust <keyid>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:253
msgid "Key IDs can be email addresses, names, or (preferably) fingerprints."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:256
msgid "Creating keys"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:258
msgid ""
"You may also create your own key so that you may sign your own packages using"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:260
msgid "$ spack gpg create <name> <email>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:264
msgid ""
"By default, the key has no expiration, but it may be set with the ``--"
"expires <date>`` flag. It is also recommended to add a comment as to the use "
"of the key using the ``--comment <comment>`` flag. The public half of the "
"key can also be exported for sharing with others so that they may use "
"packages you have signed using the ``--export <keyfile>`` flag. Secret keys "
"may also be later exported using the ``spack gpg export <location> "
"[<key>...]`` command."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:269
msgid "Key creation speed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:272
msgid ""
"The creation of a new GPG key requires generating a lot of random numbers. "
"Depending on the entropy produced on your system, the entire process may "
"take a long time (and may even appear to hang). Virtual machines and cloud "
"instances are particularly likely to display this behavior."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:276
msgid ""
"To speed it up, you may install tools like ``rngd``, which is usually "
"available as a package in the host OS. Another alternative is ``haveged``, "
"which can be installed on RHEL/CentOS machines."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:279
msgid ""
"`This Digital Ocean tutorial <https://www.digitalocean.com/community/"
"tutorials/how-to-setup-additional-entropy-for-cloud-servers-using-haveged>`_ "
"provides a good overview of sources of randomness."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:282
msgid "Build Cache Signing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:284
msgid ""
"By default, Spack will add a cryptographic signature to each package pushed "
"to a build cache and verify the signature when installing from a build cache."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:286
msgid ""
"Keys for signing can be managed with the :ref:`spack gpg <cmd-spack-gpg>` "
"command, as well as ``spack buildcache keys``, as mentioned above."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:288
msgid ""
"You can disable signing when pushing with ``spack buildcache push --"
"unsigned`` and disable verification when installing from any build cache "
"with ``spack install --no-check-signature``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:290
msgid ""
"Alternatively, signing and verification can be enabled or disabled on a per-"
"build-cache basis:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:292
msgid ""
"$ spack mirror add --signed <name> <url>  # enable signing and verification\n"
"$ spack mirror add --unsigned <name> <url>  # disable signing and "
"verification\n"
"\n"
"$ spack mirror set --signed <name>  # enable signing and verification for an "
"existing mirror\n"
"$ spack mirror set --unsigned <name>  # disable signing and verification for "
"an existing mirror"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:300
msgid ""
"Alternatively, you can edit the ``mirrors.yaml`` configuration file directly:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:302
msgid ""
"mirrors:\n"
"  <name>:\n"
"    url: <url>\n"
"    signed: false # disable signing and verification"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:309
msgid "See also :ref:`mirrors`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:312
msgid "Relocation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:314
msgid ""
"When using build caches across different machines, it is likely that the "
"install root is different from the one used to build the binaries."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:316
msgid ""
"To address this issue, Spack automatically relocates all paths encoded in "
"binaries and scripts to their new location upon installation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:318
msgid ""
"Note that there are some cases where this is not possible: if binaries are "
"built in a relatively short path and then installed to a longer path, there "
"may not be enough space in the binary to encode the new path. In this case, "
"Spack will fail to install the package from the build cache, and a source "
"build is required."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:321
msgid ""
"To reduce the likelihood of this happening, it is highly recommended to add "
"padding to the install root during the build, as specified in the :ref:"
"`config <config-yaml>` section of the configuration:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:323
msgid ""
"config:\n"
"  install_tree:\n"
"    root: /opt/spack\n"
"    padded_length: 128"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:332
msgid "Automatic Push to a Build Cache"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:334
msgid ""
"Sometimes it is convenient to push packages to a build cache immediately "
"after they are installed. Spack can do this by setting the ``--autopush`` "
"flag when adding a mirror:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:337
msgid "$ spack mirror add --autopush <name> <url or path>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:341
msgid "Or the ``--autopush`` flag can be set for an existing mirror:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:343
msgid ""
"$ spack mirror set --autopush <name>  # enable automatic push for an "
"existing mirror\n"
"$ spack mirror set --no-autopush <name>  # disable automatic push for an "
"existing mirror"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:348
msgid ""
"Then, after installing a package, it is automatically pushed to all mirrors "
"with ``autopush: true``. The command"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:351
msgid "$ spack install <package>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:355
msgid "will have the same effect as"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:357
msgid ""
"$ spack install <package>\n"
"$ spack buildcache push <cache> <package>  # for all caches with autopush: "
"true"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:364
msgid ""
"Packages are automatically pushed to a build cache only if they are built "
"from source."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:369
msgid "OCI / Docker V2 Registries as Build Cache"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:371
msgid ""
"Spack can also use OCI or Docker V2 registries such as Docker Hub, Quay.io, "
"Amazon ECR, GitHub Packages, GitLab Container Registry, JFrog Artifactory, "
"and others as build caches. This is a convenient way to share binaries using "
"public infrastructure or to cache Spack-built binaries in GitHub Actions and "
"GitLab CI. These registries can be used not only to share Spack binaries but "
"also to create and distribute runnable container images."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:375
msgid ""
"To get started, configure an OCI mirror using ``oci://`` as the scheme and "
"optionally specify variables that hold the username and password (or "
"personal access token) for the registry:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:377
msgid ""
"$ spack mirror add --oci-username-variable REGISTRY_USER \\\n"
"                   --oci-password-variable REGISTRY_TOKEN \\\n"
"                   my_registry oci://example.com/my_image"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:383
msgid ""
"This registers a mirror in your ``mirrors.yaml`` configuration file that "
"looks as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:385
msgid ""
"mirrors:\n"
"  my_registry:\n"
"    url: oci://example.com/my_image\n"
"    access_pair:\n"
"      id_variable: REGISTRY_USER\n"
"      secret_variable: REGISTRY_TOKEN"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:394
msgid ""
"Spack follows the naming conventions of Docker, with Docker Hub as the "
"default registry. To use Docker Hub, you can omit the registry domain:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:397
msgid "$ spack mirror add ... my_registry oci://username/my_image"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:401
msgid "From here, you can use the mirror as any other build cache:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:403
msgid ""
"$ export REGISTRY_USER=...\n"
"$ export REGISTRY_TOKEN=...\n"
"$ spack buildcache push my_registry <specs...>  # push to the registry\n"
"$ spack install <specs...>  # or install from the registry"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:412
msgid ""
"Spack defaults to ``https`` for OCI registries, and does not fall back to "
"``http`` in case of failure. For local registries which use ``http`` instead "
"of ``https``, you can specify ``oci+http://localhost:5000/my_image``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:418
msgid "Authentication with popular Container Registries"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:420
msgid ""
"Below are instructions for authenticating with some of the most popular "
"container registries. In all cases, you need to generate a (temporary) token "
"to use as the password -- this is not the same as your account password."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:424
msgid "GHCR"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:426
msgid ""
"To authenticate with GitHub Container Registry (GHCR), you can use your "
"GitHub username as the username. For the password, you can use either:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:429
msgid "A personal access token (PAT) with ``write:packages`` scope."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:430
msgid ""
"A GitHub Actions token (``GITHUB_TOKEN``) with ``packages:write`` permission."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:432
msgid ""
"See also `GitHub's documentation <https://docs.github.com/en/packages/"
"working-with-a-github-packages-registry/working-with-the-container-"
"registry>`_ and :ref:`github-actions-build-cache` below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:435
msgid "Docker Hub"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:437
msgid ""
"To authenticate with Docker Hub, you can use your Docker Hub username as the "
"username. For the password, you need to generate a personal access token "
"(PAT) on the Docker Hub website. See `Docker's documentation <https://docs."
"docker.com/security/access-tokens/>`_ for more information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:442
msgid "Amazon ECR"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:444
msgid ""
"To authenticate with Amazon ECR, you can use the AWS CLI to generate a "
"temporary password. The username is always ``AWS``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:447
msgid ""
"$ export AWS_ECR_PASSWORD=$(aws ecr get-login-password --region <region>)\n"
"$ spack mirror add \\\n"
"      --oci-username AWS \\\n"
"      --oci-password-variable AWS_ECR_PASSWORD \\\n"
"      my_registry \\\n"
"      oci://XXX.dkr.ecr.<region>.amazonaws.com/my/image"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:456
msgid ""
"See also `AWS's documentation <https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonECR/latest/"
"userguide/registry_auth.html>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:459
msgid "Azure Container Registry"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:461
msgid ""
"To authenticate with an Azure Container Registry that has RBAC enabled, you "
"can use the Azure CLI to generate a temporary password for your managed "
"identity. The username is always ``00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:464
msgid ""
"$ export AZURE_ACR_PASSWORD=$(az acr login --name <registry-name> --expose-"
"token --output tsv --query accessToken)\n"
"$ spack mirror add \\\n"
"      --oci-username 00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000 \\\n"
"      --oci-password-variable AZURE_ACR_PASSWORD \\\n"
"      my_registry \\\n"
"      oci://<registry-name>.azurecr.io/my/image"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../binary_caches.rst:473
msgid ""
